ccines. Our research focuses on receptors on immune cells that directly recognize pathogens and trigger production of antibodies. By using novel imaging techniques we are visualizing the mechanisms of activation of these receptors by pathogens to reveal how pathogens escape immunity. In addition, we are investigating how mutations in these immune receptors contribute to the development of human lymphomas. We would like to use the outcome of this research to support the development of next-generation vaccines and anti-cancer agents.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Antibodies are a critical component of human immunity to pathogens and underlie the success of many vaccines. Antibody responses are initiated by binding of antigens to B cell antigen receptors (BCRs) on B cell surfaces, which leads to intracellular signaling, antigen internalization, and ultimately activation of B cells. While normal function of the BCR is essential for B cell immune responses, dysregulation of BCR signaling contributes to the development of systemic autoimmune diseases and B cell lymphomas. We focus on the molecular mechanisms, by which BCR initiates signaling and internalization. We are using single molecule fluorescence imaging, combined with protein structural studies, to determine the architecture of the BCR before and after antigen binding. Furthermore, we develop large-scale imaging to identify and characterize genes involved in B cell activation. We expect that these studies will lead to new insights into the earliest steps in B cell activation, providing novel targets for therapies of diseases resulting from BCR dysregulation. We are also interested in new ways of detection of influenza virus-specific B cells, which will allow future determination of the mechanisms regulating their response during influenza infection and contribute to the design of new epitope-specific vaccines.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2015-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.o